<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>WRITTEN EVIDENCE SUBMITTED BY THE NATIONAL ASSOCIATION OF SERVICE PROVIDERS IN PHYSICAL REHABILITATION</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">DIS 15</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">ritten evidence submitted by the National Association of </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Service Providers in Physical Rehabilitation</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary  : </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Introduction to  NASPIR , its mandate and role on disability in Nepal.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">he role of rehabilitation as a pre-requisite for inclusion</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">he unmet need for rehabilitation services in Nepal: data and evidence.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 69.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Recommendations for action.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">1.NASPIR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">  and its role in  disability in Nepal</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">National Association of Service Providers in Nepal (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">NASPIR) was established in 2010 in Kathmandu. It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> is a non-profitable, non-politi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">cal umbrella organization of Nepali</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> service providers involved in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> the provision of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> physical rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">NASPIR members represent 12 among the main </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> service providers in the country</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,  from all 5 development regions of Nepal. The m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">embers under this association a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> represent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> the president </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> Ashok </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Bikram</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Jairu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Vision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> the vision of NASPIR </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">is improved access to quality and equitable  rehabilitation services for the people of Nepal.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">In order to strengthen the rehabilitation  sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">NASPIR </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">advocates for  a bigger institutional engagement from the government of Nepal, promotes research and data collection on disability, and facilitates knowledge transfer  among rehabilitation providers on technical and organizational aspects ( quality assurance process, capacity building of staff).</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">NASPIR works in cooperation with the government of Nepal and international organizations working in the field of disability and physical rehabilitation .</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The availability of rehabilitation services is very recent in Nepal. Ten years ago there was no capacity to deliver specific services to persons with disabilities; however, there were several  local non-profit organizations supporting  the most marginalized groups in their  communities, such as underserved and poor groups, certain castes, and persons with disabilities.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Thanks to the support of international agencies, those local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> that are now represented by NASPIR could develop specific capacities and infrastructures </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">such as workshops for prosthesis and orthotics, but also developed community based rehabilitation (CBR) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> to reach out the most remote communities.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Those organizations and NASPIR  today continue  advocating for an inclusive society, where barriers in access to mainstream services are eliminated and specific services are available to any person in need. Thanks to its  mandate and the experience gained  in different regions of the country , NASPIR  is able  to contribute to the debate on disability and provide concrete  recommendations for the inclusion of persons with disabilities in low-income settings to the government of the UK. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> 2.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">he role of rehabilitation as a pre-requisite for inclusion</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">As</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> highlighted in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">WHO and World Bank World Report on Disability (2010), persons </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">face widespread barriers in accessing services (health, education, employment, transport as well as information). These include inadequate policies and standards, negative attitudes, lack of service provision, inadequate funding, lack of accessibility, inadequate information and communication and lack of participation in decisions that directly affect their lives.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> The link between poverty and disability has also been underlined: persons </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> with disabilities have worse hea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">lth and socioeconomic outcomes  than persons without disabilities. The more disadvantaged are usually the more severely impaired, who have very low mobility and very poor access to information and participation in decision making.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Rehabilitation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">set of measures that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">assist individuals who experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> or are likely to experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> disability to achieve and maintain optimal functioning in interaction with their environment.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Rehabilitation is a process tailored on the person, it requires a multi-disciplinary approach which usually  includes both specialized, center-based services and community-based services.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">By improving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> mobility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> through devices and exercise, p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">romoting function</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">, removing environmental barriers and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ncreasing confidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> self esteem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">, physical rehabilitation is  often a pre-requisite for inclusion. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Physical rehabilitation, like other specific services such as vocational trainings and support services, can play an important role not only in finding personalized </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">solutions, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">but also –if continuum  is present with other kinds of services- intervene early and reduce com </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">. Habilitation and rehabilitation services  are among the services that should be available with no barriers to persons with disabilities (UNCRPD, art 20 and 26).</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">3.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence on disability and rehabilitation needs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> in Nepal.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Nepal, which has a population of nearly 30 million people, went through a 10-year civil war in which some 15,000 people were killed and many others were injured and disabled. This led to an increased need for rehabilitation services, a need that was aggravated by the reduced capacity of the health system to meet normal health needs. However, conflict is not the only factor that influences the need for physical rehabilitation services, but also growing and ageing populations, increasing prevalence of chronic conditions (such as stroke and diabetes), road traffic accidents, etc., as well as other causes often related to poverty and malnutrition. According to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">WHO </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">estimates , a country with a population of Nepal’s size could have some 450,000 persons who could need different types of rehabilitation (including physical rehabilitation), and some 150,000 persons (0.5 % of the population) could need a prosthesis or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">orthosis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">. To cover the total need </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> prostheses and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">rthoses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">, approximately 50,000 individuals could need </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">assistance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> every year.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">At present, however, only a small portion (probably less than 4 % per year) of those persons who could potentially need prosthetic and orthotic rehabilitation, benefit from such services in Nepal.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Even though the country ratified the UNCRPD in 2010, little progress has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> in defining a comprehensive s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">trategy on disability including all relevant sectors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Rehabilitation falls u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">nder Ministry of Social Welfare, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> disabili</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ty remains an object of charity. R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ehabilitation must be further integrated into the health system for better early detection (safe motherhood), stimulation (early childhood), screening, referral, community based care, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">basic rehabi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">litation services at the primary health care level.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The 12 physical rehabilitation centers (PRCs) gathered under NASPIR are today the major providers of services in the country. W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ithout them, very few persons would have access to such services.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The main objectives today are to make these services more</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> equitable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">accessible  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">, in order to reach the most vulnerable groups of the population, but also to make them more autonomous from external support and move  towards a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">sustainable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> system of services.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Good pract</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ices for improved accessibility: service models</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">It is widely acknowledged that unmet needs are huge and coverage is not sufficient. Several strategies are utilized by the PRCs in the country in order to increase accessibility of services.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">links with CBR programs.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> Community Disability Workers (CDWs) assure detection and follow up of cases that need specific services at the PRCs. This is important not only because  CDWs are in the community and can easily get access to local decision makers and peer networks for support; but also because they ensure long term follow up for cases that usually are complex . </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">One of the limits of CBR services is the fact that despite being officially integrated into the scope of the Ministry of Social Welfare and some  funds being allocated, programs are not comprehensive and focus only on certain components ( livelihood, rather than empowerment) with limited </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">inpact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> on the inclusion of persons with disabilities.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Mobile teams</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">: this  is a widespread model in Nepal given the proportion of isolated communities and the limited number of health facilities. Rehabilitation mobile camps are organized periodically by PRCs and allow the provision of rehabilitation services in areas that are highly underserved. Along the years, several modifications have been made to increase the quality and the effectiveness of such a service model. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">It has been noticed that mobile camps serve the  double purpose of both providing specific services but also raising awareness among the community and the health system of the need for  such services. In some cases, it led certain communities at the district level to make clear demands for physiotherapy services at the local hospital, with technical back up of the PRCs for the most complex cases.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Good practices for improved sustainability</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Development of a  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">ehabilitation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">anagement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">ystem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> (RMS)</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">RMS is a systematic approach to the evaluation and planning </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">physical rehabilitation facilities in core management areas identified through literature review: service users, service outputs, internal management, staff, finances</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">. RMS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">  includes the evaluation of  quality assurance mechanisms against international standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> . It was introduced in 2012 to  5 PRCs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> which were  exposed to it for the first time. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Thanks to a participatory analysis by the staff of PRCs, areas of weakness were identified and steps were taken to improve certain standards. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">However, dimensions such as human resources management  and professional performance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">highly depend</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> on environmental /national arrangements ( policies and laws on staff, academic requirements for professionals, training capacities ) that are currently far </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">from being</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> defined and endorsed on a large scale. In other words, RMS is contributing to the improvement of  local partners’ governance mechanism</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> -includ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> quality control- by introducing for the first time a sustainable instrument, yet structural weaknesses at the national level currently represent a barrier for  a more comprehensive regulation of services.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Technical sustainability:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Individual  staff assessments are regularly done by senior</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">  rehabilitation staff ( one physiotherapist </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">and one </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">specialist in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">rosthetics and Orthotics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">. These are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> rigorous evaluations of clinical and professional skills </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">against </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">a common check list of knowledge, skills and attitudes based on job profiles </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Once the evaluations are done, an individualized plan is designed to address the weaknesses and respond to the demand of the staff themselves. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">There are limitations in this approach of course, since professional regulation, accreditation and continuous professional development mechanisms are not in place in Nepal, except for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">PTs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> to some extent. It is also important to mention that policies on human resources for the rehabilitation sector don’t exist in the country. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">It is important to remember that  even  at the global level, shared standards and guidelines of reference  for the sector are missing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> and only recently WHO urged the development of such guidelines and established an action plan for  the production of evidence and recommendations  based on the 6 blocks of health system strengthening. This should allow rehabilitation stakeholders worldwide to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">answer to questions such as: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">what are the requirements of a rehabilitation service? Which standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> should be used</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">? W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">hat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> means and w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">hat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> resources are needed to respond to the disability burden in  each country ?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Financial sustainability</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Physical rehabilitation centers  receive funds from international donors, and only  limited funding   from the government. The latter is on a medium term-basis, not on comprehensive budgeting strategies.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Another source of funding   is the mobilization of local resources ( Ministry of Local Development) based on quotas for marginalized groups , but this funding is  of course limited. Attempts to develop  cost-recovery systems are  in place  and are  based on vulnerability criteria of clients (with vulnerable people  eligible for free services) , but  this only partially covers  the costs of PRCs.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">NASPIR is advocating at the central level to increase engagement of the government in allocating resources for  PRCs. However, this will require several intermediate steps such as a more detailed analysis of health and rehabilitation needs ( still unclear) , long-term planning for human resources, and the development of links between those centers and the health system.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Reccommendations for action</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> </span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:14pt; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.4pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Rehabilitation is a process that is deeply connected to  all phases of health care: from health promotion , to prevention, to care and palliative care. Once the functional links between existing rehabilitation services and both   primary health care and post-acute care are  strengthened, access to specific services will   improve and the quality of interventions will be enhanced thanks to early interventions and continuum of care for all people in need.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Given the burden of disease in the country, rehabilitation should be considered among public health strategies to reduce such burden and improve the quality of life of people.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">In practice, this would mean having a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">health system strengthening approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">: provide training to all health staff on disability; increase referral systems; carefully plan to train and deploy human resources for rehabilitation  according to the health priorities.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The overall aim should be to have a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">sector development approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> with long term plans .</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 22.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:14pt; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.4pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Inclusive  health and health –related rehabilitation system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> : measures to eliminate barriers to access to services by people with different kinds of impairments (physical, sensorial, intellectual) should be taken in a systematic way, for example: sensitizing health staff to eliminate discrimination , stigma and improve communication skill; and making health messages and facilities accessible. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:14pt; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.4pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> Besides center-based rehabilitation, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">community-based rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> is highly recommended as an effective approach to mobilize local resources , empower persons with disabilities in their own communities, and create effective links with the nearest services. This includes p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">eer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">peer support groups among persons with disabilities and support to the family members</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">. CBR is also the recommended approach to implement the UNCRPD since the components of empowerment, health, livelihood, social and education are all there, to ensure a full participation of persons living with disabilities into the society.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 22.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:14pt; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.4pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">At the level of PRCs, it is important to develop managerial capacities for better autonomy. This should include quality control mechanisms and of course planning and monitoring capacities. Regarding quality control,  parallel work on standards and professional requirements should be done at the central level .</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>